    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1968-10-29T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1968-10-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="453"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d453">
                <head>453. Memorandum From <persName corresp="#p_LSW1" type="from">Samuel W.
                        Lewis</persName> of the National Security Council Staff to the President’s
                    Special Assistant (<persName corresp="#p_RWW1" type="to">Rostow</persName>)<note
                        n="1" type="source" xml:id="d453fn1">Source: Johnson Library, National
                        Security File, Country File, Panama, Vol. X (part 3 of 3), May–December
                        1968. Confidential; Limdis.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Panama City</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1968-10-29">October 29, 1968</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">Walt—</p>
                <p>Tom Mann talked with Bill Bowdler yesterday about<persName>Arias</persName>. At
                        <persName>Arias</persName>’ request, <persName corresp="#p_MTC1"
                        >Mann</persName> spent an hour with him on Sunday morning. <persName
                        corresp="#p_MTC1">Mann</persName>’s record of the meeting is attached.<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d453fn2">Attached was an October 28 memorandum prepared by
                            <persName corresp="#p_MTC1">Mann</persName> of his meeting with
                            <persName>Arias</persName> on October 26.</note>
                </p>
                <pb facs="1003" n="958" xml:id="pg_958"/>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_MTC1">Mann</persName> feels that we should do our best to
                    continue being nice to <persName>Arias</persName>, to the extent possible,
                    because he and his followers will continue to be important in Panamanian
                    politics. <persName corresp="#p_MTC1">Mann</persName> thinks we will have to
                    retain <persName>Arias</persName>’ goodwill if we are ever to get a canal treaty
                    which can be ratified by Panama.</p>
                <p>So far, no US officials except Bob Anderson have talked with
                        <persName>Arias</persName>, although <persName corresp="#p_OCT1">Covey
                        Oliver</persName> has been prepared to see him if he asked. <persName
                        corresp="#p_MTC1">Mann</persName> is suggesting some kind of “hand-holding”
                    by State may be in order. I’ve discussed this with <persName corresp="#p_OCT1"
                        >Oliver</persName>’s Deputy, Pete Vaky, in <persName corresp="#p_OCT1"
                        >Oliver</persName>’s absence, and they are thinking it over. There are
                    obvious risks because of <persName>Arias</persName>’ unpredictability and the
                    way in which he may distort any such contacts.</p>
                <p>Incidentally, an <gloss target="#t_FBI1">FBI</gloss> report suggests
                        <persName>Arias</persName> is attempting to arrange for air and sea
                    transportation back to Panama.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LSW1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Sam</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
